{"tid":360575,"cid":5,"subCid":0,"title":"青瓦台警告美國須就任何對朝軍事行動取得南韓授權","createTime":"2017-08-15T11:56:07.000Z","updateTime":"2017-08-15T16:01:07.000Z","uid":4783,"like":1,"dislike":28,"uniUserReply":0,"replies":[{"pid":"86e1d9b38e8bb3e0c1574804d54d13fb1410de9d","tid":360575,"uid":4783,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2017-08-15T11:56:07.000Z","msg":"Updated Aug. 15, 2017 6:39 a.m. ET<br />\n<br />\nSEOUL&mdash;South Korea&rsquo;s president warned that the U.S. would need Seoul&rsquo;s consent for any military action on the Korean Peninsula and renewed calls for talks with the North, addressing the country&rsquo;s concerns about becoming ground zero for a catastrophic war it didn&rsquo;t start.<br />\n<br />\nThe comments by President Moon Jae-in followed a week of brinksmanship that ended Monday when North Korea backed away from a threat to fire missiles at Guam.<br />\n<br />\nIn a message that appeared to be aimed at Washington, he said that allied military action could only be taken on the Korean peninsula with the consent of South Korea, an implicit signal that Mr. Moon wouldn&rsquo;t tolerate any unilateral action by the U.S. to strike North Korea. It reflected the difficult situation the new president finds himself in at the center of a crisis driven by other countries.<br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;War must never break out again on the Korean peninsula. Only the Republic of Korea can make the decision for military action on the Korean peninsula,&rdquo; he said, using the country&rsquo;s formal name.<br />\n<br />\nThe U.S. Embassy in Seoul declined to comment on the speech. There was no immediate reaction from North Korean state media.<br />\n<br />\nsource：WSJ<br />\n<a href=\"https://www.wsj.com/articles/seoul-warns-u-s-against-unilateral-military-action-against-north-korea-1502781287\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Farticles%2Fseoul-warns-u-s-against-unilateral-military-action-against-north-korea-1502781287&